Title:
Red Team Grimoire

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- A multi-project repository collecting offensive Windows tradecraft focused on credential access, stealthy execution, and EDR/AV evasion.  
- It includes an advanced LSASS dumping workflow (Doppelganger) featuring PPL bypass and “clone lsass.exe then dump” style techniques to reduce direct interaction with the protected process.  
- It provides classic and modern injection/execution primitives such as process hollowing (HollowReaper) and a shellcode artifact/builder (Charon) for packaging and delivery.  
- The core evasion component (Obolos) emphasizes payload-agnostic stealth via dynamic indirect syscalls and synthetic stack manipulation to evade user-mode hooks/telemetry.  
- PowerShell utilities cover Kerberos ticket injection (TGTConjuring) and offline registry hive dumping via Volume Shadow Copies (NecroMirror), plus an LSASS dumper script (SoulDumper).  
- Useful primarily for red teamers, pentesters, and malware developers; also valuable to blue teams for understanding detection surfaces around LSASS access, syscall evasion, and Kerberos abuse.

Technical Focus:
- LSASS dumping and PPL (Protected Process Light) bypass
- Dynamic indirect syscalls (user-mode hook evasion)
- Synthetic stack / call stack spoofing (“stack weaving”)
- Process hollowing / code injection
- Kerberos TGT injection (ticket manipulation)
- Volume Shadow Copy-based SAM/SYSTEM/SECURITY hive dumping

Use Cases:
- Dumping credentials from LSASS in environments with PPL/EDR protections
- Building and delivering shellcode artifacts for controlled execution
- Executing payloads via process hollowing to blend into benign processes
- Evading user-mode API hooks using indirect syscalls and stack spoofing
- Injecting Kerberos tickets for lateral movement/impersonation in AD
- Offline credential/material extraction from registry hives via VSS

Keywords:
LSASS, PPL, Protected Process Light, credential dumping, process hollowing, shellcode loader, indirect syscalls, dynamic syscall resolution, synthetic stack, call stack spoofing, EDR evasion, AV bypass, Kerberos, TGT injection, pass-the-ticket, Volume Shadow Copy, SAM, SECURITY hive, SYSTEM hive, Windows internals